**Retrieval‑augmented generation (RAG)** is a two‑step architecture that lets a large language model (LLM) “look up” external information before it writes a response.

| Stage | What happens | Key pieces |
|-------|--------------|------------|
| **1. Retrieval** | The user query is encoded into a vector and compared to vectors of pre‑processed document chunks that live in a *vector database* (or other index). The most similar chunks are returned. | • Embedding model (creates semantic vectors)  <br>• Vector store / index  <br>• Retriever (similarity search) |
| **2. Generation** | The retrieved text is concatenated with the original query (prompt‑augmentation) and fed to the LLM, which genera
